Q: "Some football fans admire various clubs, others love only a single team. But who is a fan of whom precisely? The following argument pertains to this question: To start with, every admirer of AZ Alkmaar is neither a follower of FC Spartak Moskva nor a fan of PFC Ludogorets 1945. Now, every fan of Inverness Caledonian Thistle FC is either a follower of FC Spartak Moskva or a fan of PFC Ludogorets 1945, or both. It follows that being a fan of Inverness Caledonian Thistle FC is sufficient for not being an admirer of AZ Alkmaar."
 Is the argument, given the explicitly stated premises, deductively valid or invalid?
A:

Q: "Consumer research aims at understanding whether users of some products also tend to consume other ones, or not. The following argument seeks to clarify some such relations: First, everyone who is not both an infrequent user of René Furterer shampoo and an owner of a Proactiv soap is a regular consumer of Pears soap. Second, some frequent consumer of Dettol soap is a regular consumer of Pears soap. Therefore, some frequent consumer of Dettol soap is not both an infrequent user of René Furterer shampoo and an owner of a Proactiv soap."
 Is the argument, given the explicitly stated premises, deductively valid or invalid?
A:

Q: "Here comes a perfectly valid argument: First of all, it is not the case that Daniel is a son of Kevin. Next, no workmate of Desmond and no grandson of Chad is a son of Kevin. Therefore, Daniel is a workmate of Desmond or a grandson of Chad."
 Is the argument, given the explicitly stated premises, deductively valid or invalid?
A:

Q: "Is Fred a fan of Liverpool? Are supporters of Real Madrid devotees of PSG? In European football, it is sometimes difficult to keep track of the mutual admiration and dislike. The following argument seeks to clarify some such relations: To begin with, every devotee of FC Pyunik who is an ex-fan of Manchester City FC is not a member of FK Jablonec. All this entails that every member of FK Jablonec is neither a devotee of FC Pyunik nor an ex-fan of Manchester City FC."
 Is the argument, given the explicitly stated premises, deductively valid or invalid?
A:

Q: "Is Fred a cousin of Robert? Is Joe related to Bob? In large families, it is sometimes difficult to keep track of all one's relatives. The following argument seeks to clarify some such relations: Nobody is neither a schoolmate of Herbert nor a classmate of Matthew. Martin is a schoolmate of Herbert. It follows that it is false that Martin is a classmate of Matthew."
 Is the argument, given the explicitly stated premises, deductively valid or invalid?
A:

Q: "Is Titanium oxide an ingredient of my washing power? Which chemicals does my perfume contain? It is really difficult to keep track of all chemicals one is regularly exposed to. The following argument seeks to clarify some such relations: First premise: Every ingredient of Bioglitz Color 1N is not an ingredient of Precision Lip Liner or not an ingredient of HD Cream Liner. Second premise: Being an ingredient of Bioglitz Color 1N is necessary for being an ingredient of 05 FRUITY LIPSTICK. From this follows: Everything that is an ingredient of 05 FRUITY LIPSTICK is also an ingredient of HD Cream Liner and an ingredient of Precision Lip Liner."
 Is the argument, given the explicitly stated premises, deductively valid or invalid?
A:
